		I ran into a lot of problems in the last days because most of the logs aren't verbose enough and don't have a stack-trace. We're using the Android-Log-class (http://developer.android.com/reference/android/util/Log.html, which is ok), but with methods with a signature like (String, String). There are also methods with (String, String, Throwable) that prints out a stack-trace (needs more resources than only an error-message, I think). Alternatively we can use our own Logging-class, that uses a debug-flag (one compiled and one in settings, so you can override the compiled option). Here is a short draft: public class Logger
{
    private Logger() {}

    public static void log(final int priority, final String msg, final Throwable tr)
    {
        if (globalDebugFlag || settingsDebugFlag)
        {
            // "cgeo" instead of "cgSettings.tag"
            Log.println(priority, "cgeo", msg + "\n" + Log.getStackTraceString(tr));
        }
    }

    public static void v(final String msg, final Throwable tr)
    {
        log(Log.VERBOSE, msg, tr);
    }

    // ...
    // all methods also without Throwable
}

		The indices in my database are: CREATE INDEX in_a on cg_caches (geocode);
CREATE INDEX in_b on cg_caches (guid);
CREATE INDEX in_c on cg_caches (reason);
CREATE INDEX in_d on cg_caches (detailed);
CREATE INDEX in_e on cg_caches (type);
CREATE INDEX in_f on cg_caches (visiteddate, detailedupdate); Many indices as missing as compared to what cgCache.cgDbHelper.onCreate intends to create. But this code tries to create separate indices using the same name (in_a for example). Since if not exists is used, later indices are not created. This probably contributes to the slowness of the database.

		In getMatch(), we try to avoid keeping large strings in memory (such as a whole web page) when we only need a small part by using an explicit String constructor, in a way similar to     final String newString = new String(oldString); However, when looking at Android sources (through my CyanogenMod checked out copy), I noticed that this constructor is implemented as     public String(String string) {
        value = string.value;
        offset = string.offset;
        count = string.count;
    } which defeats the purpose, value being the real storage. To avoid keeping long strings around, if this is needed, we may have to use something like    final String newString = new String(oldString.getBytes()) Comments, thoughts?

		Please look at the following code and give feedback. I summarized a few of my ideas for a better data-handling from the last weeks. // Cache "GC23456" is already present in the database. This will load it.
Cache cache1 = new Cache("GC23456").load();

// Now we can access it in the normal way.
cache1.getName();
cache1.getCoordinates();

// We don't need it any more, so delete it.
cache1.delete();

// Please note: cache1 still has all data (we might store it agein later)
// If you don't need the object anymore, give it to the garbage collector.



// Well, now we'll load a cache, that was never opened before.
Cache cache2 = new Cache("GC2AB45").load();

// This will load the cache automatically with the connector/adapter
// (internally selected in the ORM-driver).
// It is automatically added to an internal cache (not the one you're searching)

// Storing the cache is easy. Simply call
cache2.save();

// Now it's stored in the default list. But what, if we want another list?
cache2.setListId(22);
cache2.save();



// A big problem before was storing of whole lists of caches. This took ages
// because we stored every cache with it's own request. Each request is very
// expensive (remember: it's sqlite!).
CacheList list = new CacheList();
list.add(cache1);
list.add(cache2);
list.save();

// That's all! CacheList.save() uses e.g. prepared statements in the ORM-backend
// to merge all contained caches into a single request.

// Also mass-operations are possible. Imagine you want to add a list of caches to
// a specific list.
list.setListId(10); // calls the method for every contained cache
list.save();

// Please note: CacheList is _not_ the type of list that the user selects in
// c:geo (it's only a data model), but it can be used for it.

// Maybe we can also add lazy evaluation (CacheList.lazyLoad(20)), so that only the
// first 20 caches are loaded at the beginning and the remaining ones when they're
// used. Cache as well as CacheList are working with the ORM-pattern. Internally they access a static/singleton storage-layer, that bind's adapters for platform-connectors, different databases etc.

		I would like to add a save action to our shared settings for the formatter, so that control statements are always reformatted as block. So instead of if (changed)
    notifyChanged(); I would always like to have if (changed) {
    notifyChanged();
} To me the second version is much more fault tolerant regarding later changes of the code (e.g. adding a second statement to the then-block). Any objections to having this as shared setting?

		We have a lot of code looking like: if (listOfWaypoint != null) {
  for (final cgWaypoint wp : listOfWaypoint) {
    if (wp != null) {
      …
    }
  }
} Most of the time, the list cannot contain null. And most of the time, the list cannot be null. There are a lot of places where we could cleanup the code by removing useless null checks.

