		On Navigate menu, there are already some options for navigation that are shown only if specific application is installed, for example OruxMaps. Could you please add another option, the "Pebble watch"? The application for pebble and android app are already usable. They are available on the following link: https://github.com/WebMajstr-/pebble-cgeo In near future they will be also added to Google Play store and Pebble store that will presumably start in next weeks. Additionally, I've also prepared the code for C:Geo that communicates with Pebble app and should be inserted in cgeo.geocaching.apps.cache.navi package, so implementing this change should be really fast for you :) package cgeo.geocaching.apps.cache.navi;

import cgeo.geocaching.Geocache;
import cgeo.geocaching.R;
import cgeo.geocaching.geopoint.Geopoint;

import android.app.Activity;
import android.content.Intent;

class PebbleApp extends AbstractPointNavigationApp {

    private static final String INTENT = "com.webmajstr.pebble_gc.NAVIGATE_TO";
    private static final String PACKAGE_NAME = "com.webmajstr.pebble_gc";

    PebbleApp() {
        super(getString(R.string.cache_menu_pebble), R.id.cache_app_pebble, INTENT, PACKAGE_NAME);
    }

    @Override
    public void navigate(Activity activity, Geopoint point) {
        final Intent pebbleIntent = new Intent(INTENT);
        pebbleIntent.putExtra("latitude", point.getLatitude());
        pebbleIntent.putExtra("longitude", point.getLongitude());
        activity.startActivity(pebbleIntent);
    }

    @Override
    public void navigate(Activity activity, Geocache cache) {
        final Intent pebbleIntent = new Intent(INTENT);
        pebbleIntent.putExtra("latitude", cache.getCoords().getLatitude());
        pebbleIntent.putExtra("longitude", cache.getCoords().getLongitude());
        pebbleIntent.putExtra("difficulty", cache.getDifficulty());
        pebbleIntent.putExtra("terrain", cache.getTerrain());
        pebbleIntent.putExtra("name", cache.getName());
        pebbleIntent.putExtra("code", cache.getGeocode());
        pebbleIntent.putExtra("size", cache.getSize().getL10n());
        activity.startActivity(pebbleIntent);
    }

}

		Today a user told me that c:geo shows "0 m/h" as the speed. That's not miles per hour, but meters per hour. getSpeed() calls getDistanceFromKilometers() which calls scaleDistance():             if (distanceKilometers >= 1) {
                distance = distanceKilometers;
                units = "km";
            } else {
                distance = distanceKilometers * 1000;
                units = "m";
            } That means that the string will contain m/h as long as the speed is below 1 km/h. It looks like this behavior is intended.             TestSettings.setUseImperialUnits(false);
            assertSpeed("123 km/h", 122.782f);
            assertSpeed("123 km/h", 123.456f);
            assertSpeed("12.3 km/h", 12.3456f);
            assertSpeed("1.23 km/h", 1.23456f);
            assertSpeed("123 m/h", 0.123456f);
            TestSettings.setUseImperialUnits(true);
            assertSpeed("76.7 mph", 123.456f);
            assertSpeed("7.67 mph", 12.3456f);
